<p>Orange wine represents one of the world's oldest winemaking traditions, predating both red and white wine production by millennia. This ancient technique originated in the <strong>Caucasus region</strong>, particularly in what is now Georgia, around 6,000-8,000 years ago. Archaeological evidence from sites like Gadachrili Gora reveals that early winemakers fermented white grapes with their skins in large clay vessels called <em>qvevri</em>, buried underground for temperature control.</p>

