<p>While orange wine never disappeared from Georgia, it experienced a remarkable renaissance beginning in the 1990s. Pioneering Italian winemaker <strong>Josko Gravner</strong> visited Georgia and brought qvevri techniques back to Friuli, inspiring a generation of natural wine producers. Slovenian producer Stanko Radikon simultaneously developed his own skin-contact methods, creating wines that challenged conventional white winemaking.</p>

<p>The technique spread rapidly through Austria's Burgenland, where producers like <strong>Claus Preisinger</strong> and <strong>Judith Beck</strong> embraced extended maceration. Today, orange wine production spans from Australia's Adelaide Hills to Oregon's Willamette Valley, with notable expressions from <span class="text-wine-700">Ribolla Gialla, Pinot Grigio, Gewürztraminer, and Saperavi</span>.</p>

