    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality orange wines typically range from $25-60, with exceptional bottles reaching $80-120. Entry-level options from producers like Clai or Radikon's basic cuvées start around $20-25, while premium selections from Gravner or Vodopivec can exceed $100. The higher prices reflect labor-intensive skin contact fermentation, lower yields, and the specialized expertise required for this ancient winemaking technique.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive orange wines actually better than affordable ones?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Price often correlates with complexity and aging potential in orange wines, but not always with immediate enjoyment. A $60 Gravner Ribolla Gialla will offer profound tertiary aromas and 20+ year aging potential, while a $25 Crno Vino Chardonnay delivers excellent skin-contact character for current drinking. The best value lies in finding producers who specialize in orange wine rather than those making it as an afterthought.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which regions offer the best value for orange wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Slovenia's Brda region and Georgia's Kakheti offer exceptional orange wine values, with complex, traditional-method bottles often priced 30-50% below comparable Italian or Austrian producers. Emerging regions like Sicily's Mount Etna and Australia's Adelaide Hills also provide excellent quality-to-price ratios. Avoid overpriced "natural wine trend" bottles from regions without traditional skin-contact expertise.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I tell if an orange wine is overpriced?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red flags include vague marketing language about "natural" processes without technical details, prices above $40 for first-time orange wine producers, and bottles from regions with no skin-contact tradition. Research the producer's experience with skin maceration, look for specific fermentation details (days of skin contact, vessel type), and compare prices with established producers like Radikon or Dario Princic from the same vintage.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should beginners start with expensive or affordable orange wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Start with mid-range bottles ($30-45) from established producers like Kabaj or Zidarich to understand quality orange wine characteristics without overwhelming tannins or funk. Avoid both cheap, poorly-made examples that taste oxidized and ultra-premium aged bottles that require developed palates. Focus on Pinot Grigio or Sauvignon Blanc-based orange wines, which tend to be more approachable than Ribolla Gialla or Malvasia.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest pricing mistake people make with orange wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is assuming all skin-contact wines justify premium pricing, leading buyers to overpay for mediocre bottles from trendy producers. Many restaurants mark up orange wines excessively (300-400%) banking on novelty factor. Always research the producer's traditional methods, skin contact duration, and regional reputation rather than buying based on Instagram-worthy labels or sommelier hype alone.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are aged orange wines worth the higher price?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Well-aged orange wines from quality producers develop extraordinary complexity—honeyed textures, dried fruit, and mineral depth that justify higher prices. However, many orange wines are best consumed within 3-5 years of release, making aged bottles a risky investment unless from proven producers like Gravner, Vodopivec, or Georgian qvevri specialists. Always verify proper storage conditions before paying premium prices for older vintages.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
